# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algae
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The **10th edition of *Systema Naturae*** (Latin; the English title is *A General System of Nature*) is a book written by Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus and published in two volumes in 1758 and 1759, which marks the starting point of zoological nomenclature.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In it, Linnaeus introduced binomial nomenclature for animals, something he had already done for plants in his 1753 publication of *Species Plantarum*.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Before 1758, most biological catalogues had used polynomial names for the taxa included, including earlier editions of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The first work to consistently apply binomial nomenclature across the animal kingdom was the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature therefore chose 1 January 1758 as the "starting point" for zoological nomenclature and asserted that the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae* was to be treated as if published on that date.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Names published before that date are unavailable, even if they would otherwise satisfy the rules.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The only work which takes priority over the 10th edition is Carl Alexander Clerck's **Svenska Spindlar** or **Aranei Suecici**, which was published in 1757, but is also to be treated as if published on January 1, 1758.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] During Linnaeus' lifetime, *Systema Naturae* was under continuous revision.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Progress was incorporated into new and ever-expanding editions; for example, in his 1st edition (1735), whales and manatees were originally classified as species of fish (as was thought to be the case then).
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In the 10th edition, they were both moved into the mammal class.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The animal kingdom, as described by Linnaeus: "Animals enjoy sensation by means of a living organization, animated by a medullary substance; perception by nerves; and motion by the exertion of the will.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They have members for the different purposes of life; organs for their different senses; and faculties (or powers) for the application of their different perceptions.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The list has been broken down into the original six classes Linnaeus described for animals: **Mammalia**, **Aves**, **Amphibia**, **Pisces**, **Insecta**, and **Vermes**.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] By current standards Pisces and Vermes are informal groupings, Insecta also contained arachnids and crustaceans, and one order of Amphibia comprised sharks, lampreys, and sturgeons.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described mammals as: "Animals that suckle their young by means of lactiferous teats.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In external and internal structure they resemble man: most of them are quadrupeds; and with man, their natural enemy, inhabit the surface of the Earth.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described birds as: "A beautiful and cheerful portion of created nature consisting of animals having a body covered with feathers and down; protracted and naked jaws (the beak), two wings formed for flight, and two feet.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described fish as: "Always inhabiting the waters; are swift in their motion and voracious in their appetites.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They breathe by means of gills, which are generally united by a bony arch; swim by means of radiate fins, and are mostly covered over with cartilaginous scales.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described his "Vermes" as: "Animals of slow motion, soft substance, able to increase their bulk and restore parts which have been destroyed, extremely tenacious of life, and the inhabitants of moist places.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Many of them are without a distinct head, and most of them without feet.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They are principally distinguished by their tentacles (or feelers).
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The second volume, published in 1759, detailed the kingdom Plantae, in which Linnaeus included true plants, as well as fungi, algae and lichens.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In addition to repeating the species he had previously listed in his *Species Plantarum* (1753), and those published in the intervening period, Linnaeus described several hundred new plant species.
[src:algae/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The species from *Species Plantarum* were numbered sequentially, while the new species were labelled with letters.
[src:algae/abalone] Other common names for abalone are ear shells, sea ears, and, now rarely, muttonfish or muttonshells in parts of Australia, ormer in the United Kingdom, perlemoen in South Africa, and pāua in New Zealand.
[src:algae/abalone] Most abalone vary in size from 20 mm (0.8 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (8 in).
[src:algae/abalone] The largest species, *Haliotis rufescens*, reaches 300 mm (12 in).
[src:algae/abalone] The shells of abalone have a low, open spiral structure, and are characterized by several open respiratory pores in a row near the shell's outer edge.
[src:algae/abalone] The thick inner layer of the shell is composed of nacre, which in many species is highly iridescent, giving rise to a range of strong, changeable colors which make the shells attractive to humans as ornaments, jewelry, and as a source of colorful mother-of-pearl.
[src:algae/abalone] The shell of abalone is convex, rounded to oval in shape, and may be highly arched or very flattened.
[src:algae/abalone] The shell of the majority of species has a small, flat spire and two to three whorls.
[src:algae/abalone] The last whorl, known as the body whorl, is auriform, meaning that the shell resembles an ear, giving rise to the common name "ear shell".
[src:algae/abalone] *Haliotis asinina* has a somewhat different shape, as it is more elongated and distended.
[src:algae/abalone] The shell of *Haliotis cracherodii cracherodii* is also unusual as it has an ovate form, is imperforate, shows an exserted spire, and has prickly ribs.
[src:algae/abalone] A mantle cleft in the shell impresses a groove in the shell, in which are the row of holes characteristic of the genus.
[src:algae/abalone] These holes are respiratory apertures for venting water from the gills and for releasing sperm and eggs into the water column.
[src:algae/abalone] They make up what is known as the selenizone, which forms as the shell grows.
[src:algae/abalone] This series of eight to 38 holes is near the anterior margin.
[src:algae/abalone] The older holes are gradually sealed up as the shell grows and new holes form.
[src:algae/abalone] Each species has a typical number of open holes, between four and 10, in the selenizone.
[src:algae/abalone] The aperture of the shell is very wide and nacreous.
[src:algae/abalone] The exterior of the shell is striated and dull.
[src:algae/abalone] The color of the shell is very variable from species to species, which may reflect the animal's diet.
[src:algae/abalone] The iridescent nacre that lines the inside of the shell varies in color from silvery white, to pink, red and green-red to deep blue, green to purple.
[src:algae/abalone] The animal has fimbriated head lobes and side lobes that are fimbriated and cirrated.
[src:algae/abalone] The radula has small median teeth, and the lateral teeth are single and beam-like.
[src:algae/abalone] They have about 70 uncini, with denticulated hooks, the first four very large.
[src:algae/abalone] The rounded foot is very large in comparison to most molluscs.
[src:algae/abalone] The soft body is coiled around the columellar muscle, and its insertion, instead of being on the columella, is on the middle of the inner wall of the shell.
[src:algae/abalone] The gills are symmetrical and both well developed.
[src:algae/abalone] These snails cling solidly with their broad, muscular foot to rocky surfaces at sublittoral depths, although some species such as *Haliotis cracherodii* used to be common in the intertidal zone.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone reach maturity at a relatively small size.
[src:algae/abalone] Their fecundity is high and increases with their size, laying from 10,000 to 11 million eggs at a time.
[src:algae/abalone] The spermatozoa are filiform and pointed at one end, and the anterior end is a rounded head.
[src:algae/abalone] The adults are herbivorous and feed with their rhipidoglossan radula on macroalgae, preferring red or brown algae.
[src:algae/abalone] Sizes vary from 20 mm (25⁄32 in) (*Haliotis pulcherrima*) to 200 mm (7+7⁄8 in), while *Haliotis rufescens* is the largest of the genus at 30 cm (12 in).
[src:algae/abalone] The haliotid family has a worldwide distribution, along the coastal waters of every continent, except the Pacific coast of South America, the Atlantic coast of North America, the Arctic, and Antarctica.
[src:algae/abalone] The majority of abalone species are found in cold waters, such as off the coasts of New Zealand, South Africa, Australia, Western North America, and Japan.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone are members of the clade Vetigastropoda, though their precise position within the clade is uncertain.
[src:algae/abalone] Despite their inclusion in the order Lepetellida, they do not appear to be particularly closely related to other members of the order and may be more closely related to Trochoidea, or alternatively outside of a clade uniting Trochoidea with the rest of Lepetellida.
[src:algae/abalone] The earliest known fossil abalone are known from the Campanian age of the Late Cretaceous.
[src:algae/abalone] The few known Cretaceous abalone fossils have all been found in North America, suggesting that the group may have originated there, although other possibilities have been suggested, including a central Indo-Pacific origin based on where abalone are most diverse today.
[src:algae/abalone] Haliotidae may have evolved from the pleurotomariidan families Temnotropidae or Trochotomidae.
[src:algae/abalone] *Trochotoma frydai*, from the Campanian of Spain, closely resembles the Cretaceous abalone *Haliotis antillesensis* except in having a slit instead of a row of tremata.
[src:algae/abalone] The shell of the abalone is exceptionally strong and is composed of a tightly packed calcium carbonate matrix.
[src:algae/abalone] Layered among the matrix is an endogenous protein further strengthening the shell.
[src:algae/abalone] Due to the unique structure of the shell, a force applied directly to the shell matrix will more likely cause the shedding of layers as opposed to cracking or shattering.
[src:algae/abalone] Material scientists are currently studying this structure for insight into stronger ablative protective tools such as body armor.
[src:algae/abalone] The dust created by grinding and cutting abalone shell is dangerous; appropriate safeguards must be taken to protect people from inhaling these particles.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone are subject to various infectious diseases.
[src:algae/abalone] The Victorian Department of Primary Industries said in 2007 that ganglioneuritis killed up to 90% of stock in affected regions.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone possess very little clotting factor, meaning even a mild to moderate skin-piercing injury can result in death from fluid loss.
[src:algae/abalone] Members of the Spionidae of the polychaetes are known as pests of abalone.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone have been harvested for seafood and aesthetics since prehistory.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone shells and associated materials, like their claw-like pearls and nacre, have been used as jewelry and for buttons, buckles and inlay.
[src:algae/abalone] These shells have been found in archaeological sites around the world, ranging from 100,000-year-old deposits at Blombos Cave in South Africa to historic Chinese abalone middens on California's Northern Channel Islands.
[src:algae/abalone] For at least 12,000 years, abalone were harvested to such an extent around the Channel Islands that shells in the area decreased in size four thousand years ago.
[src:algae/abalone] Aquafarming of abalone as a meat product began in the late 1950s and early 1960s in Japan and China.
[src:algae/abalone] Since the mid-1990s, there have been many increasingly successful endeavors to commercially farm abalone for the purpose of consumption.
[src:algae/abalone] Overfishing and poaching have reduced wild populations to such an extent that farmed abalone now supplies most of the abalone meat consumed.
[src:algae/abalone] The principal abalone farming regions are Mainland China, Taiwan, Japan and South Korea.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone is also farmed in Australia, Canada, Chile, France, Iceland, Ireland, Mexico, Namibia, New Zealand, South Africa, Spain, Thailand and the United States.
[src:algae/abalone] After trials in 2012, a commercial "sea ranch" was set up in Flinders Bay, Western Australia, to raise abalone.
[src:algae/abalone] The ranch is based on an artificial reef made up of 5,000 separate concrete abalone habitat units, which can host 400 abalone each.
[src:algae/abalone] The reef is seeded with young abalone from an onshore hatchery.
[src:algae/abalone] The abalone feed on seaweed that grows naturally on the habitats; the ecosystem enrichment of the bay also results in growing numbers of dhufish, pink snapper, wrasse, and Samson fish among other species.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone have long been a valuable food source for humans in every area of the world where a species is abundant.
[src:algae/abalone] The meat of this mollusc is considered a delicacy in certain parts of Latin America (particularly Chile), France, New Zealand, East Asia and Southeast Asia.
[src:algae/abalone] In the Greater China region and among overseas Chinese communities, abalone is commonly known as *bao yu*, and sometimes forms part of a Chinese banquet as one of the four sea delicacies of Chinese cuisine.
[src:algae/abalone] In the same way as shark fin soup or bird's nest soup, abalone is considered a luxury item, and is traditionally reserved for celebrations.
[src:algae/abalone] In Japan, live and raw abalone are used in sushi (known as *awabi*) or served steamed, salted, boiled, chopped, or simmered in soy sauce.
[src:algae/abalone] Salted, fermented abalone entrails are the main component of *tottsuru*, a local dish from Honshū.
[src:algae/abalone] In South Korea, abalone is called *Jeonbok* and used in various recipes.
[src:algae/abalone] *Jeonbok* porridge and pan-fried abalone steak with butter are popular, but it's also commonly used in soups or ramyeon.
[src:algae/abalone] In California, US, abalone meat can be found on pizza, sautéed with caramelized mango, or in steak form dusted with cracker meal and flour.
[src:algae/abalone] As abalone became more popular and less common, the prices adjusted accordingly.
[src:algae/abalone] In the 1920s, a restaurant-served portion of abalone, about 4 ounces (110 g), would cost (in inflation adjusted dollars) about US$7; by 2004, the price had risen to US$75.
[src:algae/abalone] In the United States, prior to this time, abalone was predominantly eaten, gathered, and prepared by Chinese immigrants.
[src:algae/abalone] Before that, abalone were collected to be eaten, and used for other purposes by Native American tribes.
[src:algae/abalone] By 1900, laws were passed in California to outlaw the taking of abalone above the intertidal zone.
[src:algae/abalone] This forced the Chinese out of the market and the Japanese perfected diving, with or without gear, to enter the market.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone started to become popular in the US after the Panama–Pacific International Exposition in 1915, which exhibited 365 varieties of fish with cooking demonstrations, and a 1,300-seat dining hall.
[src:algae/abalone] Tasmania supplies about 25% of the yearly world abalone harvest.
[src:algae/abalone] Around 12,500 Tasmanians recreationally fish for blacklip and greenlip abalone.
[src:algae/abalone] For blacklip abalone, the size limit varies between 138 mm (5.4 in) for the southern end of the state and 127 mm (5.0 in) for the northern end of the state.
[src:algae/abalone] Greenlip abalone have a minimum size of 145 mm (5.7 in), except for an area around Perkins Bay in the north of the state where the minimum size is 132 millimetres (5.2 in).
[src:algae/abalone] With a recreational abalone licence, the bag limit is 10 per day, with a total possession limit of 20.
[src:algae/abalone] Scuba diving for abalone is allowed, and has a rich history in Australia.
[src:algae/abalone] (Scuba diving for abalone in the states of New South Wales and Western Australia is illegal; a free-diving catch limit of two is allowed).
[src:algae/abalone] Victoria has had an active abalone fishery since the late 1950s.
[src:algae/abalone] The state is sectioned into three fishing zones, Eastern, Central and Western, with each fisher required a zone-allocated licence.
[src:algae/abalone] Harvesting is performed by divers using surface-supplied air "hookah" systems operating from runabout-style, outboard-powered boats.
[src:algae/abalone] While the diver seeks out colonies of abalone amongst the reef beds, the deckhand operates the boat, known as working "live" and stays above where the diver is working.
[src:algae/abalone] Bags of abalone pried from the rocks are brought to the surface by the diver or by way of "shot line", where the deckhand drops a weighted rope for the catch bag to be connected then retrieved.
[src:algae/abalone] Divers measure each abalone before removing from the reef and the deckhand remeasures each abalone and removes excess weed growth from the shell.
[src:algae/abalone] Since 2002, the Victorian industry has seen a significant decline in catches, with the total allowable catch reduced from 1440 to 787 tonnes for the 2011/12 fishing year, due to dwindling stocks and most notably the abalone virus ganglioneuritis, which is fast-spreading and lethal to abalone stocks.
[src:algae/abalone] Sport harvesting of red abalone is permitted with a California fishing license and an abalone stamp card.
[src:algae/abalone] In 2008, the abalone card also came with a set of 24 tags.
[src:algae/abalone] This was reduced to 18 abalone per year in 2014, and as of 2017 the limit has been reduced to 12, only nine of which may be taken south of Mendocino County.
[src:algae/abalone] Legal-size abalone must be tagged immediately.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone may only be taken using breath-hold techniques or shorepicking; scuba diving for abalone is strictly prohibited.
[src:algae/abalone] Taking of abalone is not permitted south of the mouth of San Francisco Bay.
[src:algae/abalone] A size minimum of 7 in (180 mm) measured across the shell is in place.
[src:algae/abalone] A person may be in possession of only three abalone at any given time.
[src:algae/abalone] As of 2017, abalone season is May to October, excluding July.
[src:algae/abalone] Transportation of abalone may only legally occur while the abalone is still attached in the shell.
[src:algae/abalone] Sale of sport-obtained abalone is illegal, including the shell.
[src:algae/abalone] Only red abalone may be taken, as black, white, pink, flat, green, and pinto abalone are protected by law.
[src:algae/abalone] In 2018, the California Fish and Game Commission closed recreational abalone season due to dramatically declining populations.
[src:algae/abalone] That year, they extended the moratorium to last through April 2021.
[src:algae/abalone] Afterwards, they extended the ban for another 5 years until April 2026.
[src:algae/abalone] In December 2025 California extended the ban another 10 years until April 2036.
[src:algae/abalone] An abalone diver is normally equipped with a thick wetsuit, including a hood, bootees, and gloves, and usually also a mask, snorkel, weight belt, abalone iron, and abalone gauge.
[src:algae/abalone] Alternatively, the rock picker can feel underneath rocks at low tides for abalone.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone are mostly taken in depths from a few inches up to 10 m (33 ft); less common are freedivers who can work deeper than 10 m (33 ft).
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone are normally found on rocks near food sources such as kelp.
[src:algae/abalone] An abalone iron is used to pry the abalone from the rock before it has time to fully clamp down.
[src:algae/abalone] Divers dive from boats, kayaks, tube floats, or directly off the shore.
[src:algae/abalone] The largest abalone recorded in California is 12.34 in (31.3 cm), caught by John Pepper somewhere off the coast of San Mateo County in September 1993.
[src:algae/abalone] The mollusc *Concholepas concholepas* is often sold in the United States under the name "Chilean abalone", though it is not an abalone, but a muricid.
[src:algae/abalone] In New Zealand, abalone is called *pāua* (/ˈpaʊə/, from the Māori language).
[src:algae/abalone] *Haliotis iris* (or blackfoot pāua) is the ubiquitous New Zealand pāua, the highly polished nacre of which is extremely popular as souvenirs with its striking blue, green, and purple iridescence.
[src:algae/abalone] *Haliotis australis* and *Haliotis virginea* are also found in New Zealand waters, but are less popular than *H. iris*.
[src:algae/abalone] *Haliotis pirimoana* is a small species endemic to Manawatāwhi / the Three Kings Islands that superficially resembles *H. virginea*.
[src:algae/abalone] Like all New Zealand shellfish, recreational harvesting of *pāua* does not require a permit provided catch limits, size restrictions, and seasonal and local restrictions set by the Ministry for Primary Industries (MPI) are followed.
[src:algae/abalone] The legal recreational daily limit is 10 per diver, with a minimum shell length of 125 mm (4.9 in) for *H. iris* and 80 mm (3.1 in) for *H. australis*.
[src:algae/abalone] In addition, no person may be in possession, even on land, of more than 20 pāua or more than 2.5 kg (5.5 lb) of pāua meat at any one time.
[src:algae/abalone] Pāua can only be caught by free-diving; it is illegal to catch them using scuba gear.
[src:algae/abalone] An extensive global black market exists in collecting and exporting abalone meat.
[src:algae/abalone] This can be a particularly awkward problem where the right to harvest pāua can be granted legally under Māori customary rights.
[src:algae/abalone] When such permits to harvest are abused, it is frequently difficult to police.
[src:algae/abalone] The limit is strictly enforced by roving Ministry for Primary Industries fishery officers with the backing of the New Zealand Police.
[src:algae/abalone] Poaching is a major industry in New Zealand with many thousands being taken illegally, often undersized.
[src:algae/abalone] Convictions have resulted in seizure of diving gear, boats, and motor vehicles and fines and in rare cases, imprisonment.
[src:algae/abalone] There are five species endemic to South Africa, namely *H. parva*, *H. spadicea*, *H. queketti* and *H. speciosa*.
[src:algae/abalone] The largest abalone in South Africa, *Haliotis midae*, occurs along roughly two-thirds of the country's coastline.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone-diving has been a recreational activity for many years, but stocks are currently being threatened by illegal commercial harvesting.
[src:algae/abalone] In South Africa, all persons harvesting this shellfish need permits that are issued annually, and no abalone may be harvested using scuba gear.
[src:algae/abalone] For the last few years, however, no permits have been issued for collecting abalone, but commercial harvesting still continues as does illegal collection by syndicates.
[src:algae/abalone] In 2007, because of widespread poaching of abalone, the South African government listed abalone as an endangered species according to the CITES section III appendix, which requests member governments to monitor the trade in this species.
[src:algae/abalone] This listing was removed from CITES in June 2010 by the South African government and South African abalone is no longer subject to CITES trade controls.
[src:algae/abalone] Export permits are still required, however.
[src:algae/abalone] The abalone meat from South Africa is prohibited for sale in the country to help reduce poaching; however, much of the illegally harvested meat is sold in Asian countries.
[src:algae/abalone] As of early 2008, the wholesale price for abalone meat was approximately US$40.00 per kilogram.
[src:algae/abalone] There is an active trade in the shells, which sell for more than US$1,400 per tonne.
[src:algae/abalone] Ormers (*Haliotis tuberculata*) are considered a delicacy in the British Channel Islands as well as in adjacent areas of France, and are pursued with great alacrity by the locals.
[src:algae/abalone] This, and a recent lethal bacterial disease, has led to a dramatic depletion in numbers since the latter half of the 19th century, and "ormering" is now strictly regulated to preserve stocks.
[src:algae/abalone] The gathering of ormers is now restricted to a number of 'ormering tides', from 1 January to 30 April, which occur on the full or new moon and two days following.
[src:algae/abalone] No ormers may be taken from the beach that are under 80 millimetres (3.1 in) in shell length.
[src:algae/abalone] Gatherers are not allowed to wear wetsuits or even put their heads underwater.
[src:algae/abalone] Any breach of these laws is a criminal offence and can lead to a fine of up to £5,000 or six months in prison.
[src:algae/abalone] The demand for ormers is such that they led to the world's first underwater arrest, when Mr.
[src:algae/abalone] Kempthorne-Leigh of Guernsey was arrested by a police officer in full diving gear when illegally diving for ormers.
[src:algae/abalone] The highly iridescent inner nacre layer of the shell of abalone has traditionally been used as a decorative item, in jewelry, buttons, and as inlay in furniture and musical instruments, such as on fret boards and binding of guitars.
[src:algae/abalone] See article Najeonchilgi regarding Korean handicraft.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone has been an important staple in a number of Indigenous cultures around the world, specifically in Africa and on the Northwest American coast.
[src:algae/abalone] The meat is a traditional food, and the shell is used to make ornaments; historically, the shells were also used as currency in some communities.
[src:algae/abalone] Abalone are critically threatened due to overfishing and the acidification of oceans as lower pH erodes the calcium carbonate in their shells.
[src:algae/abalone] In the 21st century, white, pink, and green abalone are on the United States federal endangered species list.
[src:algae/abalone] Possible restoration sites have been proposed for the San Clemente Island and Santa Barbara Island areas.
[src:algae/abalone] Reintroduction of farming abalone to the wild has been proposed, with these abalone having special tags to help track the population.
[src:algae/abalone] The number of species that are recognized within the genus *Haliotis* has fluctuated over time, and depends on the source that is consulted.
[src:algae/abalone] The number of recognized species range from 30 to 130.
[src:algae/abalone] As of 2025, 76 extant species and 25 fossil species were listed as accepted in MolluscaBase.
[src:algae/abalone] This list finds a compromise using the WoRMS database, plus some species that have been added, for a total of 57.
[src:algae/abalone] The majority of abalone have not been rated for conservation status.
[src:algae/abalone] Those that have been reviewed tend to show that the abalone in general is an animal that is declining in numbers, and will need protection throughout the globe.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:algae/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:algae/acetabularia] In the 1930s–1950s Joachim Hämmerling conducted experiments in which he demonstrated *Acetabularia*'s genetic information is contained in the nucleus.
[src:algae/acetabularia] This was the first demonstration that genes are encoded by DNA in eukaryotes; earlier studies by Oswald Avery and others had shown that this was true for prokaryotes.
[src:algae/acetabularia] The name, *Acetabularia*, derives from the Latin word *acetabulum*, a broad, shallow cup used for dipping bread; the upturned cap of *Acetabularia* resembles such a cup.
[src:algae/acetabularia] For this reason, it is also sometimes called **mermaid's wineglass**.
[src:algae/acetabularia] In the 19th century, the same designation *Acetabularia* was proposed by George Edward Massee for a genus of fungi (now *Cyphellopus*), but this usage is obsolete and considered invalid as the algal name takes precedence.
[src:algae/acetabularia] Each *Acetabularia* cell is composed of three segments: the "foot" or basal segment which contains the nucleus, the "stalk", and the "cap".
[src:algae/acetabularia] Hämmerling exchanged caps between individuals from two species, *A. mediterranea* and *A. crenulata*.
[src:algae/acetabularia] *A. mediterranea* has a smooth, disc-shaped cap, while *A. crenulata* has a branched, flower-like cap.
[src:algae/acetabularia] After the exchange, each transplanted cap gradually changed from its original form to the form typical for the species of the base it was now attached to.
[src:algae/acetabularia] This showed that the nucleus controlled the form of the cap.
[src:algae/acetabularia] In another experiment, Hämmerling inserted a nucleus from one species of *Acetabularia* into an intact *Acetabularia* of a different species.
[src:algae/acetabularia] The *Acetabularia* then produced a hybrid cap with characteristics of both species.
[src:algae/acetabularia] This showed that both nuclei influenced the form of the cap.
[src:algae/acetabularia] Hammerling's results showed that the nucleus of a cell contains the genetic information that directs cellular development.
[src:algae/acetabularia] Although a single cell, *Acetabularia* exhibits a remarkably complex shape and has therefore long been a model organism for studying gene expression and morphogenesis.
[src:algae/acetabularia] It seems to transport messenger RNA molecules (in an inactive riboprotein form) from the nucleus to its apical tips, where they are translated into proteins.
[src:algae/acetabularia] These molecules may be activated by proteolysis of their protein carrier molecules, but this has not been verified as yet.
[src:algae/acetabularia] In addition to its gradient in specific mRNA molecules, *Acetabularia* exhibits concentration gradients in several types of molecules, such as ascorbic acid.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] An **action potential** (also known as a **nerve impulse** or "**spike**" when in a neuron) is a series of quick changes in voltage across a cell membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] An action potential occurs when the membrane potential of a specific cell rapidly rises and falls.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This "depolarization" (physically, a reversal of the polarization of the membrane) then causes adjacent locations to similarly depolarize.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Action potentials occur in several types of excitable cells, which include animal cells like neurons and muscle cells, as well as some plant cells.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Certain endocrine cells such as pancreatic beta cells, and certain cells of the anterior pituitary gland are also excitable cells.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In other types of cells, their main function is to activate intracellular processes.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In muscle cells, for example, an action potential is the first step in the chain of events leading to contraction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In beta cells of the pancreas, they provoke release of insulin.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The temporal sequence of action potentials generated by a neuron is called its "spike train".
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A neuron that emits an action potential, or nerve impulse, is often said to "fire".
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Action potentials are generated by special types of voltage-gated ion channels embedded in a cell's plasma membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These channels are shut when the membrane potential is near the (negative) resting potential of the cell, but they rapidly begin to open if the membrane potential increases to a precisely defined threshold voltage, "depolarising" the membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] When the channels open, they allow an inward flow of sodium ions, which makes the interior of the cell more positive, which further raises the (negative) membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This then causes more channels to open, producing a greater electric current across the cell membrane and so on.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The process proceeds explosively until all of the available ion channels are open, resulting in a large upswing in the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The rapid influx of sodium ions causes the polarity of (i.e. the direction of the electric field across) the plasma membrane to reverse, and the ion channels then rapidly inactivate.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] As the sodium channels close, sodium ions can no longer enter the neuron, and they are then actively transported back out of the plasma membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Potassium channels are then activated, and there is an outward current of potassium ions, returning the electrochemical gradient to the resting state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Because few ions need to pass through to change the potential, the concentrations of ions on either side remain relatively unchanged during this process.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] After an action potential has occurred, there is a transient negative shift, called the afterhyperpolarization.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In animal cells, there are two primary types of action potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] One type is generated by voltage-gated sodium channels, the other by voltage-gated calcium channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Sodium-based action potentials usually last for under one millisecond, but calcium-based action potentials may last for 100 milliseconds or longer.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In some types of neurons, slow calcium spikes provide the driving force for a long burst of rapidly emitted sodium spikes.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In cardiac muscle cells, on the other hand, an initial fast sodium spike provides a "primer" to provoke the rapid onset of a calcium spike, which then produces muscle contraction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Nearly all cell membranes in animals, plants and fungi maintain a voltage difference between the exterior and interior of the cell, called the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A typical voltage across an animal cell membrane is −70 mV.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This means that the interior of the cell has a negative voltage relative to the exterior.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In most types of cells, the membrane potential usually stays fairly constant.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Some types of cells, however, are electrically active in the sense that their voltages fluctuate over time.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In some types of electrically active cells, including neurons and muscle cells, the voltage fluctuations frequently take the form of a rapid upward (positive) spike followed by a rapid fall.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These up-and-down cycles are known as *action potentials*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Their duration varies considerably with the type of cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In mammalian neurons, the entire up-and-down cycle takes only a few thousandths of a second, while in plant cells, an action potential may last as long as several seconds.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The electrical properties of a cell are determined by the structure of its membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A cell membrane consists of a lipid bilayer of molecules in which larger protein molecules are embedded.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The lipid bilayer is highly resistant to movement of electrically charged ions, so it functions as an insulator.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The large membrane-embedded proteins, in contrast, provide channels through which ions can pass across the membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Action potentials are driven by channel proteins whose configuration switches between closed and open states as a function of the voltage difference between the interior and exterior of the cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These voltage-sensitive proteins are known as voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] All cells in animal body tissues are electrically polarized – in other words, they maintain a voltage difference across the cell's plasma membrane, known as the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This electrical polarization results from a complex interplay between protein structures embedded in the membrane called ion pumps and ion channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In neurons, the types of ion channels in the membrane usually vary across different parts of the cell, giving the dendrites, axon, and cell body different electrical properties.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] As a result, some parts of the membrane of a neuron may be excitable (capable of generating action potentials), whereas others are not.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Recent studies have shown that the most excitable part of a neuron is the part after the axon hillock (the point where the axon leaves the cell body), which is called the axonal initial segment, but the axon and cell body are also excitable in most cases.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Each excitable patch of membrane has two important levels of membrane potential: the resting potential, which is the value the membrane potential maintains as long as nothing perturbs the cell, and a higher value called the threshold potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At the axon hillock of a typical neuron, the resting potential is around −70 millivolts (mV) and the threshold potential is around −55 mV.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Synaptic inputs to a neuron cause the membrane to depolarize or hyperpolarize; that is, they cause the membrane potential to rise or fall.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Action potentials are triggered when enough depolarization accumulates to bring the membrane potential up to threshold.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] When an action potential is triggered, the membrane potential abruptly shoots upward and then equally abruptly shoots back downward, often ending below the resting level, where it remains for some period of time.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The shape of the action potential is stereotyped; this means that the rise and fall usually have approximately the same amplitude and time course for all action potentials in a given cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] (Exceptions are discussed later in the article) In most neurons, the entire process takes place in about a thousandth of a second.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Many types of neurons emit action potentials constantly at rates of up to 10–100 per second.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, some types are much quieter, and may go for minutes or longer without emitting any action potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Action potentials result from the presence in a cell's membrane of special types of voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At least one of the conformations creates a channel through the membrane that is permeable to specific types of ions.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The transition between conformations is influenced by the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Thus, a voltage-gated ion channel tends to be open for some values of the membrane potential, and closed for others.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In most cases, however, the relationship between membrane potential and channel state is probabilistic and involves a time delay.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Ion channels switch between conformations at unpredictable times: The membrane potential determines the rate of transitions and the probability per unit time of each type of transition.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Voltage-gated ion channels are capable of producing action potentials because they can give rise to positive feedback loops: the membrane potential controls the state of the ion channels, and the state of the ion channels controls the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Thus, in some situations, a rise in the membrane potential can cause ion channels to open, thereby causing a further rise in the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] An action potential occurs when this positive feedback cycle proceeds explosively.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The time and amplitude trajectory of the action potential are determined by the biophysical properties of the voltage-gated ion channels that produce it.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Several types of channels capable of producing the positive feedback necessary to generate an action potential do exist.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Voltage-gated sodium channels are responsible for the fast action potentials involved in nerve conduction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Slower action potentials in muscle cells and some types of neurons are generated by voltage-gated calcium channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Each of these types comes in multiple variants, with different voltage sensitivity and different temporal dynamics.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The most intensively studied type of voltage-dependent ion channels comprises the sodium channels involved in fast nerve conduction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These are sometimes known as Hodgkin-Huxley sodium channels because they were first characterized by Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley in their Nobel Prize-winning studies of the biophysics of the action potential, but can more conveniently be referred to as *Na*V channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] (The "V" stands for "voltage".) An *Na*V channel has three possible states, known as *deactivated*, *activated*, and *inactivated*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The channel is permeable only to sodium ions when it is in the *activated* state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] When the membrane potential is low, the channel spends most of its time in the *deactivated* (closed) state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If the membrane potential is raised above a certain level, the channel shows increased probability of transitioning to the *activated* (open) state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The higher the membrane potential the greater the probability of activation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Once a channel has activated, it will eventually transition to the *inactivated* (closed) state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] It tends then to stay inactivated for some time, but, if the membrane potential becomes low again, the channel will eventually transition back to the *deactivated* state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] During an action potential, most channels of this type go through a cycle *deactivated*→*activated*→*inactivated*→*deactivated*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This is only the population average behavior, however – an individual channel can in principle make any transition at any time.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, the likelihood of a channel's transitioning from the *inactivated* state directly to the *activated* state is very low: A channel in the *inactivated* state is refractory until it has transitioned back to the *deactivated* state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The outcome of all this is that the kinetics of the *Na*V channels are governed by a transition matrix whose rates are voltage-dependent in a complicated way.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Since these channels themselves play a major role in determining the voltage, the global dynamics of the system can be quite difficult to work out.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Hodgkin and Huxley approached the problem by developing a set of differential equations for the parameters that govern the ion channel states, known as the Hodgkin-Huxley equations.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These equations have been extensively modified by later research, but form the starting point for most theoretical studies of action potential biophysics.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] As the membrane potential is increased, sodium ion channels open, allowing the entry of sodium ions into the cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This is followed by the opening of potassium ion channels that permit the exit of potassium ions from the cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The inward flow of sodium ions increases the concentration of positively charged cations in the cell and causes depolarization, where the potential of the cell is higher than the cell's resting potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The sodium channels close at the peak of the action potential, while potassium continues to leave the cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The efflux of potassium ions decreases the membrane potential or hyperpolarizes the cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] For small voltage increases from rest, the potassium current exceeds the sodium current and the voltage returns to its normal resting value, typically −70 mV.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, if the voltage increases past a critical threshold, typically 15 mV higher than the resting value, the sodium current dominates.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This results in a runaway condition whereby the positive feedback from the sodium current activates even more sodium channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Thus, the cell *fires*, producing an action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The frequency at which a neuron elicits action potentials is often referred to as a **firing rate** or **neural firing rate**.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Currents produced by the opening of voltage-gated channels in the course of an action potential are typically significantly larger than the initial stimulating current.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Thus, the amplitude, duration, and shape of the action potential are determined largely by the properties of the excitable membrane and not the amplitude or duration of the stimulus.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This all-or-nothing property of the action potential sets it apart from graded potentials such as receptor potentials, electrotonic potentials, subthreshold membrane potential oscillations, and synaptic potentials, which scale with the magnitude of the stimulus.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A variety of action potential types exist in many cell types and cell compartments as determined by the types of voltage-gated channels, leak channels, channel distributions, ionic concentrations, membrane capacitance, temperature, and other factors.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The principal ions involved in an action potential are sodium and potassium cations; sodium ions enter the cell, and potassium ions leave, restoring equilibrium.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Relatively few ions need to cross the membrane for the membrane voltage to change drastically.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The ions exchanged during an action potential, therefore, make a negligible change in the interior and exterior ionic concentrations.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The few ions that do cross are pumped out again by the continuous action of the sodium–potassium pump, which, with other ion transporters, maintains the normal ratio of ion concentrations across the membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Calcium cations and chloride anions are involved in a few types of action potentials, such as the cardiac action potential and the action potential in the single-cell alga *Acetabularia*, respectively.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Although action potentials are generated locally on patches of excitable membrane, the resulting currents can trigger action potentials on neighboring stretches of membrane, precipitating a domino-like propagation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In contrast to passive spread of electric potentials (electrotonic potential), action potentials are generated anew along excitable stretches of membrane and propagate without decay.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Myelinated sections of axons are not excitable and do not produce action potentials and the signal is propagated passively as electrotonic potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Regularly spaced unmyelinated patches, called the nodes of Ranvier, generate action potentials to boost the signal.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Known as saltatory conduction, this type of signal propagation provides a favorable tradeoff of signal velocity and axon diameter.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Depolarization of axon terminals, in general, triggers the release of neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In addition, backpropagating action potentials have been recorded in the dendrites of pyramidal neurons, which are ubiquitous in the neocortex.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These are thought to have a role in spike-timing-dependent plasticity.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In the Hodgkin–Huxley membrane capacitance model, the speed of transmission of an action potential was undefined and it was assumed that adjacent areas became depolarized due to released ion interference with neighbouring channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Measurements of ion diffusion and radii have since shown this not to be possible.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Moreover, contradictory measurements of entropy changes and timing disputed the capacitance model as acting alone.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Alternatively, Gilbert Ling's adsorption hypothesis, posits that the membrane potential and action potential of a living cell is due to the adsorption of mobile ions onto adsorption sites of cells.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A neuron's ability to generate and propagate an action potential changes during development.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] How much the membrane potential of a neuron changes as the result of a current impulse is a function of the membrane input resistance.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] As a cell grows, more channels are added to the membrane, causing a decrease in input resistance.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A mature neuron also undergoes shorter changes in membrane potential in response to synaptic currents.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Neurons from a ferret lateral geniculate nucleus have a longer time constant and larger voltage deflection at P0 than they do at P30.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] One consequence of the decreasing action potential duration is that the fidelity of the signal can be preserved in response to high frequency stimulation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Immature neurons are more prone to synaptic depression than potentiation after high frequency stimulation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In the early development of many organisms, the action potential is actually initially carried by calcium current rather than sodium current.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The opening and closing kinetics of calcium channels during development are slower than those of the voltage-gated sodium channels that will carry the action potential in the mature neurons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The longer opening times for the calcium channels can lead to action potentials that are considerably slower than those of mature neurons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Xenopus neurons initially have action potentials that take 60–90 ms.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] During development, this time decreases to 1 ms.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] There are two reasons for this drastic decrease.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] First, the inward current becomes primarily carried by sodium channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Second, the delayed rectifier, a potassium channel current, increases to 3.5 times its initial strength.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In order for the transition from a calcium-dependent action potential to a sodium-dependent action potential to proceed new channels must be added to the membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If Xenopus neurons are grown in an environment with RNA synthesis or protein synthesis inhibitors that transition is prevented.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Even the electrical activity of the cell itself may play a role in channel expression.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If action potentials in Xenopus myocytes are blocked, the typical increase in sodium and potassium current density is prevented or delayed.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This maturation of electrical properties is seen across species.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Xenopus sodium and potassium currents increase drastically after a neuron goes through its final phase of mitosis.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The sodium current density of rat cortical neurons increases by 600% within the first two postnatal weeks.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Several types of cells support an action potential, such as plant cells, muscle cells, and the specialized cells of the heart (in which occurs the cardiac action potential).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, the main excitable cell is the neuron, which also has the simplest mechanism for the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Neurons are electrically excitable cells composed, in general, of one or more dendrites, a single soma, a single axon and one or more axon terminals.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Dendrites are cellular projections whose primary function is to receive synaptic signals.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Their protrusions, known as dendritic spines, are designed to capture the neurotransmitters released by the presynaptic neuron.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] They have a high concentration of ligand-gated ion channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These spines have a thin neck connecting a bulbous protrusion to the dendrite.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This ensures that changes occurring inside the spine are less likely to affect the neighboring spines.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The dendritic spine can, with rare exception (see LTP), act as an independent unit.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The dendrites extend from the soma, which houses the nucleus, and many of the "normal" eukaryotic organelles.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Unlike the spines, the surface of the soma is populated by voltage activated ion channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These channels help transmit the signals generated by the dendrites.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Emerging out from the soma is the axon hillock.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This region is characterized by having a very high concentration of voltage-activated sodium channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In general, it is considered to be the spike initiation zone for action potentials, i.e. the trigger zone.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Multiple signals generated at the spines, and transmitted by the soma all converge here.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Immediately after the axon hillock is the axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This is a thin tubular protrusion traveling away from the soma.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The axon is insulated by a myelin sheath.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Myelin is composed of either Schwann cells (in the peripheral nervous system) or oligodendrocytes (in the central nervous system), both of which are types of glial cells.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Although glial cells are not involved with the transmission of electrical signals, they communicate and provide important biochemical support to neurons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] To be specific, myelin wraps multiple times around the axonal segment, forming a thick fatty layer that prevents ions from entering or escaping the axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This insulation prevents significant signal decay as well as ensuring faster signal speed.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This insulation, however, has the restriction that no channels can be present on the surface of the axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] There are, therefore, regularly spaced patches of membrane, which have no insulation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These nodes of Ranvier can be considered to be "mini axon hillocks", as their purpose is to boost the signal in order to prevent significant signal decay.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At the furthest end, the axon loses its insulation and begins to branch into several axon terminals.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These presynaptic terminals, or synaptic boutons, are a specialized area within the axon of the presynaptic cell that contains neurotransmitters enclosed in small membrane-bound spheres called synaptic vesicles.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Before considering the propagation of action potentials along axons and their termination at the synaptic knobs, it is helpful to consider the methods by which action potentials can be initiated at the axon hillock.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The basic requirement is that the membrane voltage at the hillock be raised above the threshold for firing.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] There are several ways in which this depolarization can occur.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Action potentials are most commonly initiated by excitatory postsynaptic potentials from a presynaptic neuron.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Typically, neurotransmitter molecules are released by the presynaptic neuron.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These neurotransmitters then bind to receptors on the postsynaptic cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This binding opens various types of ion channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This opening has the further effect of changing the local permeability of the cell membrane and, thus, the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If the binding increases the voltage (depolarizes the membrane), the synapse is excitatory.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If, however, the binding decreases the voltage (hyperpolarizes the membrane), it is inhibitory.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Whether the voltage is increased or decreased, the change propagates passively to nearby regions of the membrane (as described by the cable equation and its refinements).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Typically, the voltage stimulus decays exponentially with the distance from the synapse and with time from the binding of the neurotransmitter.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Some fraction of an excitatory voltage may reach the axon hillock and may (in rare cases) depolarize the membrane enough to provoke a new action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] More typically, the excitatory potentials from several synapses must work together at nearly the same time to provoke a new action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Their joint efforts can be thwarted, however, by the counteracting inhibitory postsynaptic potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Neurotransmission can also occur through electrical synapses.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Due to the direct connection between excitable cells in the form of gap junctions, an action potential can be transmitted directly from one cell to the next in either direction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The free flow of ions between cells enables rapid non-chemical-mediated transmission.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Rectifying channels ensure that action potentials move only in one direction through an electrical synapse.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Electrical synapses are found in all nervous systems, including the human brain, although they are a distinct minority.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The amplitude of an action potential is often thought to be independent of the amount of current that produced it.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In other words, larger currents do not create larger action potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Therefore, action potentials are said to be all-or-none signals, since either they occur fully or they do not occur at all.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This is in contrast to receptor potentials, whose amplitudes are dependent on the intensity of a stimulus.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In both cases, the frequency of action potentials is correlated with the intensity of a stimulus.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In sensory neurons, an external signal such as pressure, temperature, light, or sound is coupled with the opening and closing of ion channels, which in turn alter the ionic permeabilities of the membrane and its voltage.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These voltage changes can again be excitatory (depolarizing) or inhibitory (hyperpolarizing) and, in some sensory neurons, their combined effects can depolarize the axon hillock enough to provoke action potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Some examples in humans include the olfactory receptor neuron and Meissner's corpuscle, which are critical for the sense of smell and touch, respectively.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, not all sensory neurons convert their external signals into action potentials; some do not even have an axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Instead, they may convert the signal into the release of a neurotransmitter, or into continuous graded potentials, either of which may stimulate subsequent neuron(s) into firing an action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] For illustration, in the human ear, hair cells convert the incoming sound into the opening and closing of mechanically gated ion channels, which may cause neurotransmitter molecules to be released.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In sensory neurons, action potentials result from an external stimulus.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, some excitable cells require no such stimulus to fire: They spontaneously depolarize their axon hillock and fire action potentials at a regular rate, like an internal clock.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The voltage traces of such cells are known as pacemaker potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The cardiac pacemaker cells of the sinoatrial node in the heart provide a good example.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Although such pacemaker potentials have a natural rhythm, it can be adjusted by external stimuli; for instance, heart rate can be altered by pharmaceuticals as well as signals from the sympathetic and parasympathetic nerves.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The external stimuli do not cause the cell's repetitive firing, but merely alter its timing.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In some cases, the regulation of frequency can be more complex, leading to patterns of action potentials, such as bursting.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The course of the action potential can be divided into five parts: the rising phase, the peak phase, the falling phase, the undershoot phase, and the refractory period.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] During the rising phase the membrane potential depolarizes (becomes more positive).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The point at which depolarization stops is called the peak phase.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At this stage, the membrane potential reaches a maximum.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Subsequent to this, there is a falling phase.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] During this stage the membrane potential becomes more negative, returning towards resting potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The undershoot, or afterhyperpolarization, phase is the period during which the membrane potential temporarily becomes more negatively charged than when at rest (hyperpolarized).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Finally, the time during which a subsequent action potential is impossible or difficult to fire is called the refractory period, which may overlap with the other phases.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The course of the action potential is determined by two coupled effects.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] First, voltage-sensitive ion channels open and close in response to changes in the membrane voltage *Vm*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This changes the membrane's permeability to those ions.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Second, according to the Goldman equation, this change in permeability changes the equilibrium potential *Em*, and, thus, the membrane voltage *Vm*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Thus, the membrane potential affects the permeability, which then further affects the membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This sets up the possibility for positive feedback, which is a key part of the rising phase of the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A complicating factor is that a single ion channel may have multiple internal "gates" that respond to changes in *Vm* in opposite ways, or at different rates.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] For example, although raising *Vm* *opens* most gates in the voltage-sensitive sodium channel, it also *closes* the channel's "inactivation gate", albeit more slowly.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Hence, when *Vm* is raised suddenly, the sodium channels open initially, but then close due to the slower inactivation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The voltages and currents of the action potential in all of its phases were modeled accurately by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley in 1952, for which they were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1963.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, their model considers only two types of voltage-sensitive ion channels, and makes several assumptions about them, e.g., that their internal gates open and close independently of one another.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In reality, there are many types of ion channels, and they do not always open and close independently.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A typical action potential begins at the axon hillock with a sufficiently strong depolarization, e.g., a stimulus that increases *Vm*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This depolarization is often caused by the injection of extra sodium cations into the cell; these cations can come from a wide variety of sources, such as chemical synapses, sensory neurons or pacemaker potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] For a neuron at rest, there is a high concentration of sodium and chloride ions in the extracellular fluid compared to the intracellular fluid, while there is a high concentration of potassium ions in the intracellular fluid compared to the extracellular fluid.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The difference in concentrations, which causes ions to move from a high to a low concentration, and electrostatic effects (attraction of opposite charges) are responsible for the movement of ions in and out of the neuron.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The inside of a neuron has a negative charge, relative to the cell exterior, from the movement of K+ out of the cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The neuron membrane is more permeable to K+ than to other ions, allowing this ion to selectively move out of the cell, down its concentration gradient.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This concentration gradient along with potassium leak channels present on the membrane of the neuron causes an efflux of potassium ions making the resting potential close to *E*K ≈ −75 mV.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Since Na+ ions are in higher concentrations outside of the cell, the concentration and voltage differences both drive them into the cell when Na+ channels open.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Depolarization opens both the sodium and potassium channels in the membrane, allowing the ions to flow into and out of the axon, respectively.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If the depolarization is small (say, increasing *Vm* from −70 mV to −60 mV), the outward potassium current overwhelms the inward sodium current and the membrane repolarizes back to its normal resting potential around −70 mV.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, if the depolarization is large enough, the inward sodium current increases more than the outward potassium current and a runaway condition (positive feedback) results: the more inward current there is, the more *Vm* increases, which in turn further increases the inward current.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A sufficiently strong depolarization (increase in *Vm*) causes the voltage-sensitive sodium channels to open; the increasing permeability to sodium drives *Vm* closer to the sodium equilibrium voltage *E*Na≈ +55 mV.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The increasing voltage in turn causes even more sodium channels to open, which pushes *Vm* still further towards *E*Na.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This positive feedback continues until the sodium channels are fully open and *Vm* is close to *E*Na.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The sharp rise in *Vm* and sodium permeability correspond to the *rising phase* of the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The critical threshold voltage for this runaway condition is usually around −45 mV, but it depends on the recent activity of the axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] A cell that has just fired an action potential cannot fire another one immediately, since the Na+ channels have not recovered from the inactivated state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The period during which no new action potential can be fired is called the *absolute refractory period*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At longer times, after some but not all of the ion channels have recovered, the axon can be stimulated to produce another action potential, but with a higher threshold, requiring a much stronger depolarization, e.g., to −30 mV.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The period during which action potentials are unusually difficult to evoke is called the *relative refractory period*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The positive feedback of the rising phase slows and comes to a halt as the sodium ion channels become maximally open.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At the peak of the action potential, the sodium permeability is maximized and the membrane voltage *Vm* is nearly equal to the sodium equilibrium voltage *E*Na.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, the same raised voltage that opened the sodium channels initially also slowly shuts them off, by closing their pores; the sodium channels become *inactivated*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This lowers the membrane's permeability to sodium relative to potassium, driving the membrane voltage back towards the resting value.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At the same time, the raised voltage opens voltage-sensitive potassium channels; the increase in the membrane's potassium permeability drives *Vm* towards *E*K.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Combined, these changes in sodium and potassium permeability cause *Vm* to drop quickly, repolarizing the membrane and producing the "falling phase" of the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The depolarized voltage opens additional voltage-dependent potassium channels, and some of these do not close right away when the membrane returns to its normal resting voltage.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In addition, further potassium channels open in response to the influx of calcium ions during the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The intracellular concentration of potassium ions is transiently unusually low, making the membrane voltage *Vm* even closer to the potassium equilibrium voltage *E*K.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The membrane potential goes below the resting membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Hence, there is an undershoot or hyperpolarization, termed an afterhyperpolarization, that persists until the membrane potassium permeability returns to its usual value, restoring the membrane potential to the resting state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Each action potential is followed by a refractory period, which can be divided into an *absolute refractory period*, during which it is impossible to evoke another action potential, and then a *relative refractory period*, during which a stronger-than-usual stimulus is required.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These two refractory periods are caused by changes in the state of sodium and potassium channel molecules.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] When closing after an action potential, sodium channels enter an "inactivated" state, in which they cannot be made to open regardless of the membrane potential—this gives rise to the absolute refractory period.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Even after a sufficient number of sodium channels have transitioned back to their resting state, it frequently happens that a fraction of potassium channels remains open, making it difficult for the membrane potential to depolarize, and thereby giving rise to the relative refractory period.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Because the density and subtypes of potassium channels may differ greatly between different types of neurons, the duration of the relative refractory period is highly variable.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The absolute refractory period is largely responsible for the unidirectional propagation of action potentials along axons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At any given moment, the patch of axon behind the actively spiking part is refractory, but the patch in front, not having been activated recently, is capable of being stimulated by the depolarization from the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The action potential generated at the axon hillock propagates as a wave along the axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The currents flowing inwards at a point on the axon during an action potential spread out along the axon, and depolarize the adjacent sections of its membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If sufficiently strong, this depolarization provokes a similar action potential at the neighboring membrane patches.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This basic mechanism was demonstrated by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin in 1937.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] After crushing or cooling nerve segments and thus blocking the action potentials, he showed that an action potential arriving on one side of the block could provoke another action potential on the other, provided that the blocked segment was sufficiently short.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Once an action potential has occurred at a patch of membrane, the membrane patch needs time to recover before it can fire again.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] At the molecular level, this *absolute refractory period* corresponds to the time required for the voltage-activated sodium channels to recover from inactivation, i.e., to return to their closed state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] There are many types of voltage-activated potassium channels in neurons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] On the other hand, all neuronal voltage-activated sodium channels inactivate within several milliseconds during strong depolarization, thus making following depolarization impossible until a substantial fraction of sodium channels have returned to their closed state.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Although it limits the frequency of firing, the absolute refractory period ensures that the action potential moves in only one direction along an axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The currents flowing in due to an action potential spread out in both directions along the axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, only the unfired part of the axon can respond with an action potential; the part that has just fired is unresponsive until the action potential is safely out of range and cannot restimulate that part.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In the usual orthodromic conduction, the action potential propagates from the axon hillock towards the synaptic knobs (the axonal termini); propagation in the opposite direction—known as antidromic conduction—is very rare.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, if a laboratory axon is stimulated in its middle, both halves of the axon are "fresh", i.e., unfired; then two action potentials will be generated, one traveling towards the axon hillock and the other traveling towards the synaptic knobs.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] To enable fast and efficient transduction of electrical signals in the nervous system, certain neuronal axons are covered with myelin sheaths.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Myelin is a multilamellar membrane that enwraps the axon in segments separated by intervals known as nodes of Ranvier.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] It is produced by specialized cells: Schwann cells exclusively in the peripheral nervous system, and oligodendrocytes exclusively in the central nervous system.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Myelin sheath reduces membrane capacitance and increases membrane resistance in the inter-node intervals, thus allowing a fast, saltatory movement of action potentials from node to node.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Myelination is found mainly in vertebrates, but an analogous system has been discovered in a few invertebrates, such as some species of shrimp.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Not all neurons in vertebrates are myelinated; for example, axons of the neurons comprising the autonomic nervous system are not, in general, myelinated.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Myelin prevents ions from entering or leaving the axon along myelinated segments.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] As a general rule, myelination increases the conduction velocity of action potentials and makes them more energy-efficient.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Whether saltatory or not, the mean conduction velocity of an action potential ranges from 1 meter per second (m/s) to over 100 m/s, and, in general, increases with axonal diameter.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Action potentials cannot propagate through the membrane in myelinated segments of the axon.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, the current is carried by the cytoplasm, which is sufficient to depolarize the first or second subsequent node of Ranvier.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Instead, the ionic current from an action potential at one node of Ranvier provokes another action potential at the next node; this apparent "hopping" of the action potential from node to node is known as saltatory conduction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Although the mechanism of saltatory conduction was suggested in 1925 by Ralph Lillie, the first experimental evidence for saltatory conduction came from Ichiji Tasaki and Taiji Takeuchi and from Andrew Huxley and Robert Stämpfli.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] By contrast, in unmyelinated axons, the action potential provokes another in the membrane immediately adjacent, and moves continuously down the axon like a wave.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Myelin has two important advantages: fast conduction speed and energy efficiency.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] For axons larger than a minimum diameter (roughly 1 micrometre), myelination increases the conduction velocity of an action potential, typically tenfold.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Conversely, for a given conduction velocity, myelinated fibers are smaller than their unmyelinated counterparts.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] For example, action potentials move at roughly the same speed (25 m/s) in a myelinated frog axon and an unmyelinated squid giant axon, but the frog axon has a roughly 30-fold smaller diameter and 1000-fold smaller cross-sectional area.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Also, since the ionic currents are confined to the nodes of Ranvier, far fewer ions "leak" across the membrane, saving metabolic energy.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] This saving is a significant selective advantage, since the human nervous system uses approximately 20% of the body's metabolic energy.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The length of axons' myelinated segments is important to the success of saltatory conduction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] They should be as long as possible to maximize the speed of conduction, but not so long that the arriving signal is too weak to provoke an action potential at the next node of Ranvier.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In nature, myelinated segments are generally long enough for the passively propagated signal to travel for at least two nodes while retaining enough amplitude to fire an action potential at the second or third node.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Thus, the safety factor of saltatory conduction is high, allowing transmission to bypass nodes in case of injury.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] However, action potentials may end prematurely in certain places where the safety factor is low, even in unmyelinated neurons; a common example is the branch point of an axon, where it divides into two axons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Some diseases degrade myelin and impair saltatory conduction, reducing the conduction velocity of action potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The most well-known of these is multiple sclerosis, in which the breakdown of myelin impairs coordinated movement.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] The flow of currents within an axon can be described quantitatively by cable theory and its elaborations, such as the compartmental model.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Cable theory was developed in 1855 by Lord Kelvin to model the transatlantic telegraph cable and was shown to be relevant to neurons by Hodgkin and Rushton in 1946.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In simple cable theory, the neuron is treated as an electrically passive, perfectly cylindrical transmission cable, which can be described by a partial differential equation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] where *V*(*x*, *t*) is the voltage across the membrane at a time *t* and a position *x* along the length of the neuron, and where λ and τ are the characteristic length and time scales on which those voltages decay in response to a stimulus.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] Referring to the circuit diagram on the right, these scales can be determined from the resistances and capacitances per unit length.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] These time and length-scales can be used to understand the dependence of the conduction velocity on the diameter of the neuron in unmyelinated fibers.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] For example, the time-scale τ increases with both the membrane resistance *rm* and capacitance *cm*.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] As the capacitance increases, more charge must be transferred to produce a given transmembrane voltage (by the equation *Q* = *CV*); as the resistance increases, less charge is transferred per unit time, making the equilibration slower.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] In a similar manner, if the internal resistance per unit length *ri* is lower in one axon than in another (e.g., because the radius of the former is larger), the spatial decay length λ becomes longer and the conduction velocity of an action potential should increase.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p01] If the transmembrane resistance *rm* is increased, that lowers the average "leakage" current across the membrane, likewise causing *λ* to become longer, increasing the conduction velocity.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] In general, action potentials that reach the synaptic knobs cause a neurotransmitter to be released into the synaptic cleft.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Neurotransmitters are small molecules that may open ion channels in the postsynaptic cell; most axons have the same neurotransmitter at all of their termini.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The arrival of the action potential opens voltage-sensitive calcium channels in the presynaptic membrane; the influx of calcium causes vesicles filled with neurotransmitter to migrate to the cell's surface and release their contents into the synaptic cleft.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This complex process is inhibited by the neurotoxins tetanospasmin and botulinum toxin, which are responsible for tetanus and botulism, respectively.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Some synapses dispense with the "middleman" of the neurotransmitter, and connect the presynaptic and postsynaptic cells together.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] When an action potential reaches such a synapse, the ionic currents flowing into the presynaptic cell can cross the barrier of the two cell membranes and enter the postsynaptic cell through pores known as connexons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Thus, the ionic currents of the presynaptic action potential can directly stimulate the postsynaptic cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Electrical synapses allow for faster transmission because they do not require the slow diffusion of neurotransmitters across the synaptic cleft.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Hence, electrical synapses are used whenever fast response and coordination of timing are crucial, as in escape reflexes, the retina of vertebrates, and the heart.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] A special case of a chemical synapse is the neuromuscular junction, in which the axon of a motor neuron terminates on a muscle fiber.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] In such cases, the released neurotransmitter is acetylcholine, which binds to the acetylcholine receptor, an integral membrane protein in the membrane (the *sarcolemma*) of the muscle fiber.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] However, the acetylcholine does not remain bound; rather, it dissociates and is hydrolyzed by the enzyme, acetylcholinesterase, located in the synapse.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This enzyme quickly reduces the stimulus to the muscle, which allows the degree and timing of muscular contraction to be regulated delicately.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Some poisons inactivate acetylcholinesterase to prevent this control, such as the nerve agents sarin and tabun, and the insecticides diazinon and malathion.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The cardiac action potential differs from the neuronal action potential by having an extended plateau, in which the membrane is held at a high voltage for a few hundred milliseconds prior to being repolarized by the potassium current as usual.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This plateau is due to the action of slower calcium channels opening and holding the membrane voltage near their equilibrium potential even after the sodium channels have inactivated.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The cardiac action potential plays an important role in coordinating the contraction of the heart.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The cardiac cells of the sinoatrial node provide the pacemaker potential that synchronizes the heart.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The action potentials of those cells propagate to and through the atrioventricular node (AV node), which is normally the only conduction pathway between the atria and the ventricles.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Action potentials from the AV node travel through the bundle of His and thence to the Purkinje fibers.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Conversely, anomalies in the cardiac action potential—whether due to a congenital mutation or injury—can lead to human pathologies, especially arrhythmias.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Several anti-arrhythmia drugs act on the cardiac action potential, such as quinidine, lidocaine, beta blockers, and verapamil.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The action potential in a normal skeletal muscle cell is similar to the action potential in neurons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Action potentials result from the depolarization of the cell membrane (the sarcolemma), which opens voltage-sensitive sodium channels; these become inactivated and the membrane is repolarized through the outward current of potassium ions.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The resting potential prior to the action potential is typically −90mV, somewhat more negative than typical neurons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The muscle action potential lasts roughly 2–4 ms, the absolute refractory period is roughly 1–3 ms, and the conduction velocity along the muscle is roughly 5 m/s.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The action potential releases calcium ions that free up the tropomyosin and allow the muscle to contract.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Muscle action potentials are provoked by the arrival of a pre-synaptic neuronal action potential at the neuromuscular junction, which is a common target for neurotoxins.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Plant and fungal cells are also electrically excitable.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The fundamental difference from animal action potentials is that the depolarization in plant cells is not accomplished by an uptake of positive sodium ions, but by release of negative *chloride* ions.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Bose published the first measurements of action potentials in plants, which had previously been discovered by Burdon-Sanderson and Darwin.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] An increase in cytoplasmic calcium ions may be the cause of anion release into the cell.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This makes calcium a precursor to ion movements, such as the influx of negative chloride ions and efflux of positive potassium ions, as seen in barley leaves.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The initial influx of calcium ions also poses a small cellular depolarization, causing the voltage-gated ion channels to open and allowing full depolarization to be propagated by chloride ions.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] *Dionaea muscipula*) use sodium-gated channels to operate plant movements and "count" stimulation events to determine if a threshold for movement is met.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] *Dionaea muscipula*, also known as the Venus flytrap, is found in subtropical wetlands in North and South Carolina.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] When there are poor soil nutrients, the flytrap relies on a diet of insects and animals.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Despite research on the plant, there lacks an understanding behind the molecular basis to the Venus flytraps, and carnivore plants in general.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] However, plenty of research has been done on action potentials and how they affect movement and clockwork within the Venus flytrap.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] To start, the resting membrane potential of the Venus flytrap (−120 mV) is lower than animal cells (usually −90 mV to −40 mV).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The lower resting potential makes it easier to activate an action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Thus, when an insect lands on the trap of the plant, it triggers a hair-like mechanoreceptor.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This receptor then activates an action potential that lasts around 1.5 ms.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This causes an increase of positive calcium ions into the cell, slightly depolarizing it.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] However, the flytrap does not close after one trigger.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Instead, it requires the activation of two or more hairs.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] If only one hair is triggered, it disregards the activation as a false positive.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Further, the second hair must be activated within a certain time interval (0.75–40 s) for it to register with the first activation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Thus, a buildup of calcium begins and then slowly falls after the first trigger.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] When the second action potential is fired within the time interval, it reaches the calcium threshold to depolarize the cell, closing the trap on the prey within a fraction of a second.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Together with the subsequent release of positive potassium ions the action potential in plants involves an osmotic loss of salt (KCl).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Whereas, the animal action potential is osmotically neutral because equal amounts of entering sodium and leaving potassium cancel each other osmotically.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The interaction of electrical and osmotic relations in plant cells appears to have arisen from an osmotic function of electrical excitability in a common unicellular ancestors of plants and animals under changing salinity conditions.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Further, the present function of rapid signal transmission is seen as a newer accomplishment of metazoan cells in a more stable osmotic environment.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] It is likely that the familiar signaling function of action potentials in some vascular plants (e.g.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] *Mimosa pudica*) arose independently from that in metazoan excitable cells.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Unlike the rising phase and peak, the falling phase and after-hyperpolarization seem to depend primarily on cations that are not calcium.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] To initiate repolarization, the cell requires movement of potassium out of the cell through passive transportation on the membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This differs from neurons because the movement of potassium does not dominate the decrease in membrane potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] To fully repolarize, a plant cell requires energy in the form of ATP to assist in the release of hydrogen from the cell – utilizing a transporter called proton ATPase.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Action potentials are found throughout multicellular organisms, including plants, invertebrates such as insects, and vertebrates such as reptiles and mammals.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Sponges seem to be the main phylum of multicellular eukaryotes that does not transmit action potentials, although some studies have suggested that these organisms have a form of electrical signaling, too.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The resting potential, as well as the size and duration of the action potential, have not varied much with evolution, although the conduction velocity does vary dramatically with axonal diameter and myelination.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Given its conservation throughout evolution, the action potential seems to confer evolutionary advantages.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] One function of action potentials is rapid, long-range signaling within the organism; the conduction velocity can exceed 110 m/s, which is one-third the speed of sound.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] For comparison, a hormone molecule carried in the bloodstream moves at roughly 8 m/s in large arteries.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Part of this function is the tight coordination of mechanical events, such as the contraction of the heart.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] A second function is the computation associated with its generation.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Being an all-or-none signal that does not decay with transmission distance, the action potential has similar advantages to digital electronics.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The integration of various dendritic signals at the axon hillock and its thresholding to form a complex train of action potentials is another form of computation, one that has been exploited biologically to form central pattern generators and mimicked in artificial neural networks.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The common prokaryotic/eukaryotic ancestor, which lived perhaps four billion years ago, is believed to have had voltage-gated channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] This functionality was likely, at some later point, cross-purposed to provide a communication mechanism.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Even modern single-celled bacteria can utilize action potentials to communicate with other bacteria in the same biofilm.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The study of action potentials has required the development of new experimental methods.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The initial work, prior to 1955, was carried out primarily by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Fielding Huxley, who were, along John Carew Eccles, awarded the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their contribution to the description of the ionic basis of nerve conduction.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] It focused on three goals: isolating signals from single neurons or axons, developing fast, sensitive electronics, and shrinking electrodes enough that the voltage inside a single cell could be recorded.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The first problem was solved by studying the giant axons found in the neurons of the squid (*Loligo forbesii* and *Doryteuthis pealeii*, at the time classified as *Loligo pealeii*).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] These axons are so large in diameter (roughly 1 mm, or 100-fold larger than a typical neuron) that they can be seen with the naked eye, making them easy to extract and manipulate.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] However, they are not representative of all excitable cells, and numerous other systems with action potentials have been studied.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Since the current equals *C* times the rate of change of the transmembrane voltage *Vm*, the solution was to design a circuit that kept *Vm* fixed (zero rate of change) regardless of the currents flowing across the membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Thus, the current required to keep *Vm* at a fixed value is a direct reflection of the current flowing through the membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Other electronic advances included the use of Faraday cages and electronics with high input impedance, so that the measurement itself did not affect the voltage being measured.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The third problem, that of obtaining electrodes small enough to record voltages within a single axon without perturbing it, was solved in 1949 with the invention of the glass micropipette electrode, which was quickly adopted by other researchers.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Refinements of this method are able to produce electrode tips that are as fine as 100 Å (10 nm), which also confers high input impedance.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Action potentials may also be recorded with small metal electrodes placed just next to a neuron, with neurochips containing EOSFETs, or optically with dyes that are sensitive to Ca2+ or to voltage.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] While glass micropipette electrodes measure the sum of the currents passing through many ion channels, studying the electrical properties of a single ion channel became possible in the 1970s with the development of the patch clamp by Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] For this discovery, they were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1991.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Patch-clamping verified that ionic channels have discrete states of conductance, such as open, closed and inactivated.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Optical imaging technologies have been developed in recent years to measure action potentials, either via simultaneous multisite recordings or with ultra-spatial resolution.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Using voltage-sensitive dyes, action potentials have been optically recorded from a tiny patch of cardiomyocyte membrane.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Several neurotoxins, both natural and synthetic, function by blocking the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Tetrodotoxin from the pufferfish and saxitoxin from the *Gonyaulax* (the dinoflagellate genus responsible for "red tides") block action potentials by inhibiting the voltage-sensitive sodium channel; similarly, dendrotoxin from the black mamba snake inhibits the voltage-sensitive potassium channel.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Such inhibitors of ion channels serve an important research purpose, by allowing scientists to "turn off" specific channels at will, thus isolating the other channels' contributions; they can also be useful in purifying ion channels by affinity chromatography or in assaying their concentration.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] However, such inhibitors also make effective neurotoxins, and have been considered for use as chemical weapons.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Neurotoxins aimed at the ion channels of insects have been effective insecticides; one example is the synthetic permethrin, which prolongs the activation of the sodium channels involved in action potentials.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The ion channels of insects are sufficiently different from their human counterparts that there are few side effects in humans.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The role of electricity in the nervous systems of animals was first observed in dissected frogs by Luigi Galvani, who studied it from 1791 to 1797.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Galvani's results inspired Alessandro Volta to develop the Voltaic pile—the earliest-known electric battery—with which he studied animal electricity (such as electric eels) and the physiological responses to applied direct-current voltages.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] In the 19th century scientists studied the propagation of electrical signals in whole nerves (i.e., bundles of neurons) and demonstrated that nervous tissue was made up of cells, instead of an interconnected network of tubes (a *reticulum*).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Carlo Matteucci followed up Galvani's studies and demonstrated that injured nerves and muscles in frogs could produce direct current.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Matteucci's work inspired the German physiologist, Emil du Bois-Reymond, who discovered in 1843 that stimulating these muscle and nerve preparations produced a notable diminution in their resting currents, making him the first researcher to identify the electrical nature of the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The conduction velocity of action potentials was then measured in 1850 by du Bois-Reymond's friend, Hermann von Helmholtz.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Progress in electrophysiology stagnated thereafter due to the limitations of chemical theory and experimental practice.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] To establish that nervous tissue is made up of discrete cells, the Spanish physician Santiago Ramón y Cajal and his students used a stain developed by Camillo Golgi to reveal the myriad shapes of neurons, which they rendered painstakingly.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] For their discoveries, Golgi and Ramón y Cajal were awarded the 1906 Nobel Prize in Physiology.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Their work resolved a long-standing controversy in the neuroanatomy of the 19th century; Golgi himself had argued for the network model of the nervous system.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The 20th century saw significant breakthroughs in electrophysiology.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] In 1902 and again in 1912, Julius Bernstein advanced the hypothesis that the action potential resulted from a change in the permeability of the axonal membrane to ions.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Bernstein's hypothesis was confirmed by Ken Cole and Howard Curtis, who showed that membrane conductance increases during an action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] In 1907, Louis Lapicque suggested that the action potential was generated as a threshold was crossed, what would be later shown as a product of the dynamical systems of ionic conductances.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] In 1949, Alan Hodgkin and Bernard Katz refined Bernstein's hypothesis by considering that the axonal membrane might have different permeabilities to different ions; in particular, they demonstrated the crucial role of the sodium permeability for the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] They made the first actual recording of the electrical changes across the neuronal membrane that mediate the action potential.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Hodgkin and Huxley correlated the properties of their mathematical model with discrete ion channels that could exist in several different states, including "open", "closed", and "inactivated".
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Their hypotheses were confirmed in the mid-1970s and 1980s by Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann, who developed the technique of patch clamping to examine the conductance states of individual ion channels.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] In the 21st century, researchers are beginning to understand the structural basis for these conductance states and for the selectivity of channels for their species of ion, through the atomic-resolution crystal structures, fluorescence distance measurements and cryo-electron microscopy studies.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Julius Bernstein was also the first to introduce the Nernst equation for resting potential across the membrane; this was generalized by David E.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Goldman to the eponymous Goldman equation in 1943.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The sodium–potassium pump was identified in 1957 and its properties gradually elucidated, culminating in the determination of its atomic-resolution structure by X-ray crystallography.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The crystal structures of related ionic pumps have also been solved, giving a broader view of how these molecular machines work.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] Mathematical and computational models are essential for understanding the action potential, and offer predictions that may be tested against experimental data, providing a stringent test of a theory.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The most important and accurate of the early neural models is the Hodgkin–Huxley model, which describes the action potential by a coupled set of four ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] The properties of the Hodgkin–Huxley and FitzHugh–Nagumo models and their relatives, such as the Bonhoeffer–Van der Pol model, have been well-studied within mathematics, computation and electronics.
[src:algae/action-potentials-p02] However the simple models of generator potential and action potential fail to accurately reproduce the near threshold neural spike rate and spike shape, specifically for the mechanoreceptors like the Pacinian corpuscle.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Aerobiologists have traditionally been involved in the measurement and reporting of airborne pollen and fungal spores as a service to those with allergies.
[src:algae/aerobiology] However, aerobiology is a varied field, relating to environmental science, plant science, meteorology, phenology, and climate change.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The first mention of "aerobiology" was made by Fred Campbell Meier in the 1930s.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The particles, which can be described as Aeroplankton, generally range in size from nanometers to micrometers which makes them challenging to detect.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Aerosolization is the process of small and light particles becoming suspended in moving air.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Now bioaerosols, these pollen and fungal spores can be transported across an ocean, or even travel around the globe.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Due to the high quantities of microbes and the ease of dispersion, Martinus Beijerinck once said "Everything is everywhere, the environment selects".
[src:algae/aerobiology] This means that aeroplankton are everywhere and have been everywhere, and it solely depends on environmental factors to determine which remain.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Aeroplankton are found in significant quantities even in the Atmospheric boundary layer (ABL).
[src:algae/aerobiology] The effects on climate and cloud chemistry of these atmospheric populations is still under review.
[src:algae/aerobiology] NASA and other research agencies are studying how long these bioaerosols can remain afloat and how they can survive in such extreme climates.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The conditions of the upper atmosphere are similar to the climate on Mars' surface, and the microbes found are helping redefine the conditions which can support life.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The process of dispersal of aerobiological particles has 3 steps: removal from source, dispersion through air, and deposition to rest.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The particle geometry and environment affect all three phases, however once it is aerosolized, its fate depends on the laws of physics governing the motion of the air.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Pollen and spores can be blown from their surface or shaken loose.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Generally the wind speed required for release is higher than average wind speed.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Some fungi can even be triggered by environmental factors to actively eject spores.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Once released from rest, the aeroplankton is at the mercy of the wind and physics.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The settling speed of spores and pollen vary and is a major factor in dispersion; the longer the particle is floating, the longer it can be caught by a turbulent wind gust.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Wind speed and direction fluctuate with time and height, so the specific path of once neighboring particles can vary significantly.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The concentration of particles in the air decreases with distance from source, and the dispersion distance is most accurately modeled as a power function.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Deposition is a combination of gravity and inertia.
[src:algae/aerobiology] The fall speed for small particles can be calculated by mass and geometry, but the complex shapes of pollen and spores often fall slower than their estimated speed modeled with simple shapes.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Spores can also be removed from the air from impact; the inertia of the particles will cause them to hit surfaces along their path, instead of flowing around them like air.
[src:algae/aerobiology] There have been many studies performed to understand real-life dispersal patterns of pollen and spores.
[src:algae/aerobiology] To collect samples, studies often use a volumetric spore trap such as a Hirst-type sampler.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Particles stick to a sampling strip and then can be inspected under a microscope.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Scientists have to count the particles under magnification, and then analyze sample DNA by Amplicon sequence variant (ASV) or another common method.
[src:algae/aerobiology] A challenge repeatedly cited in literature is that because of differing testing or analysis methodologies, results are not always comparable across studies.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Therefore, extensive data collection must be performed in each study to get an accurate model.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Unfortunately there is no database of aerobiological particle distribution to compare results to.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Allergic rhinitis is a type of inflammation in the nose that occurs when the immune system overreacts to allergens in the air.
[src:algae/aerobiology] It is typically triggered in humans by pollen and other bioaerosols.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Between 10% and 30% of people in Western countries are affected.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Symptoms are usually worse during pollination periods, when there is significantly more pollen aerosolized in the air.
[src:algae/aerobiology] In these peak periods, staying indoors is one way to limit exposure.
[src:algae/aerobiology] However, studies have shown that there are still significant levels of pollen indoors.
[src:algae/aerobiology] In the winter, pollen levels indoors actually exceed outdoor levels.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Up to date data on pollen levels is critical for humans that have allergies.
[src:algae/aerobiology] A current limitation is that many spore traps require scientists to identify and count individual pollen grains under magnification.
[src:algae/aerobiology] This causes data to be delayed, sometimes by over a week.
[src:algae/aerobiology] There are currently a number of fully automatic spore traps in development, and once they are fully functional they will improve the lives of people with allergies.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Scientists have predicted that the meteorological results of climate change will weaken pollen and spore dispersal barriers, and lead to less biological uniqueness in different regions.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Precipitation increases richness (number of species) of biodiversity in regions because clouds formulate in the upper atmosphere where there is more varied biodiversity.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Specifically in the Arctic, climate change has dramatically increased precipitation, and scientists have seen new microbes in the area because of it.
[src:algae/aerobiology] Rising summer temperatures and CO2 levels have shown to increase total amounts of pollen released by certain trees, as well as delay the start of pollen season.
[src:algae/aerobiology] However, more studies are needed to see long term effects of climate change.
[src:algae/aerophyte] The **Raunkiær system** is a system for categorizing plants using life-form categories, devised by Danish botanist Christen C.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Raunkiær and later extended by various authors.
[src:algae/aerophyte] It was first proposed in a talk to the *Danish Botanical Society* in 1904 as can be inferred from the printed discussion of that talk, but not the talk itself, nor its title.
[src:algae/aerophyte] The journal, *Botanisk Tidsskrift*, published brief comments on the talk by M.
[src:algae/aerophyte] A fuller account appeared in French the following year.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Raunkiær elaborated further on the system and published this in Danish in 1907.
[src:algae/aerophyte] The original note and the 1907 paper were much later translated to English and published in 1934 with Raunkiær's collected works.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Raunkiær's life-form scheme has subsequently been revised and modified by various authors, but the main structure has survived.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Raunkiær's life-form system may be useful in researching the transformations of biotas and the genesis of some groups of phytophagous animals.
[src:algae/aerophyte] These plants, normally woody perennials, grow stems into the air, with their resting buds being more than 50 cm above the soil surface, e.g. trees and shrubs, and also epiphytes, which Raunkiær later separated as a distinct class (see below).
[src:algae/aerophyte] Further division was premised on the characters of duration of foliage, i. e. evergreen or deciduous, and presence of covering bracts on buds, for 12 classes.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Epiphytes were originally included in the phanerophytes (see above) but then separated because they do not grow in soil, so the soil location is irrelevant in classifying them.
[src:algae/aerophyte] They form characteristic communities of moist climatic conditions.
[src:algae/aerophyte] These plants have buds on persistent shoots near the soil surface; woody plants with perennating buds borne close to the soil surface, a maximum of 25 cm above the soil surface, e.g., bilberry and periwinkle.
[src:algae/aerophyte] These are annual plants that complete their lives rapidly in favorable conditions and survive the unfavorable cold or dry season in the form of seeds.
[src:algae/aerophyte] About 6% of plants are therophytes but their proportion is much higher in regions with a hot, dry summer.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Aerophytes were a later addition to the system.
[src:algae/aerophyte] These are plants that obtain moisture and nutrients from the air and rain.
[src:algae/aerophyte] They usually grow on other plants yet are not parasitic on them.
[src:algae/aerophyte] These are perennial plants and are like epiphytes but whose root system have been reduced.
[src:algae/aerophyte] They occur in communities that inhabit exclusively hyper-arid areas with abundant fog.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Like epiphytes and hemicryptophytes, their buds are near the soil surface.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Some *Tillandsia* species are classified as aerophytes.
[src:algae/aerophyte] Farley Mowat, in his book, *Never Cry Wolf*, described using a Raunkiær's Circle in making a "cover degree" study to determine the ratios of various plants one to the other.
[src:algae/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:algae/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:algae/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:algae/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:algae/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:algae/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:algae/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:algae/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:algae/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:algae/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:algae/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:algae/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:algae/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:algae/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:algae/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:algae/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:algae/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:algae/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:algae/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:algae/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:algae/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:algae/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:algae/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:algae/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:algae/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:algae/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:algae/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:algae/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:algae/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:algae/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:algae/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:algae/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:algae/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:algae/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:algae/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:algae/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:algae/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:algae/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:algae/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:algae/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:algae/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:algae/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:algae/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:algae/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:algae/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:algae/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:algae/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:algae/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:algae/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:algae/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:algae/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:algae/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:algae/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:algae/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:algae/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:algae/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:algae/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:algae/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:algae/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:algae/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:algae/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:algae/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:algae/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:algae/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:algae/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:algae/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:algae/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:algae/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:algae/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:algae/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:algae/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:algae/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:algae/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:algae/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:algae/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:algae/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:algae/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:algae/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:algae/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:algae/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:algae/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:algae/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:algae/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:algae/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:algae/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:algae/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:algae/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:algae/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:algae/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:algae/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:algae/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:algae/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:algae/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:algae/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:algae/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:algae/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:algae/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:algae/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:algae/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:algae/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:algae/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:algae/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:algae/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:algae/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:algae/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:algae/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:algae/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:algae/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:algae/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:algae/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:algae/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:algae/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:algae/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:algae/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:algae/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:algae/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:algae/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:algae/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:algae/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:algae/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:algae/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:algae/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:algae/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:algae/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:algae/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:algae/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:algae/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:algae/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:algae/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:algae/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:algae/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:algae/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:algae/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:algae/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:algae/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:algae/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:algae/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:algae/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:algae/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:algae/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:algae/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:algae/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:algae/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:algae/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:algae/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:algae/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:algae/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:algae/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:algae/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:algae/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:algae/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:algae/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:algae/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:algae/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:algae/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:algae/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:algae/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:algae/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:algae/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:algae/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:algae/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:algae/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:algae/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:algae/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:algae/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:algae/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:algae/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:algae/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:algae/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:algae/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:algae/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:algae/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:algae/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:algae/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:algae/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:algae/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:algae/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:algae/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:algae/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:algae/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:algae/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:algae/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:algae/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:algae/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:algae/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:algae/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:algae/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:algae/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:algae/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:algae/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:algae/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:algae/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:algae/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:algae/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:algae/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:algae/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:algae/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:algae/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:algae/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:algae/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:algae/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:algae/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:algae/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:algae/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:algae/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:algae/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:algae/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:algae/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:algae/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:algae/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:algae/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:algae/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:algae/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:algae/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:algae/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:algae/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:algae/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:algae/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:algae/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:algae/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:algae/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:algae/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:algae/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:algae/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:algae/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:algae/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:algae/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:algae/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:algae/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:algae/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:algae/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:algae/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:algae/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:algae/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:algae/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:algae/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:algae/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:algae/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:algae/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:algae/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
